He studied law at McGill University (MU) where he earned of Bachelor of Arts in 1930.
While a student there he notably wrote the MU's annual Red and White Revue in 1926 and 1927.
In 1927 he co-wrote the review The Little Revue that Starts at 10 Past Nine with Robert E. Dolan which was premiered at the Orpheum in Vancouver.
In 1929 Davis began working for CBC Radio as a pianist and conductor.
He left the CBC to establish his own production house in Montreal in 1948.
He notably conducted the studio orchestra for a 1962 LP album with accordionist Gordie Fleming.
From 1937-1947 he worked as a music producer at CBC Montreal where he notably arranged music for conductors like Lucio Agostini, Jean Deslauriers, and Allan McIver.
